_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis unique collection of 12 research projects carried out by experienced practitioners in the play sector in the UK and USA puts forward a range of perspectives on children's play and adults' relationships with it. Drawing on a diverse range of research methodologies, the studies consider adults' memories of play; the co-production of spaces where children can play (in adventure playgrounds, out of school clubs, children’s zoos, children's museums and public space); therapeutic approaches to playwork; playwork and wellbeing; supporting the play of severely disabled children and young people; play and contemporary art practice; and children's use of technology in a playground. Offering a fresh look beyond the dominant singular voice of developmental psychology, this book is essential reading for anyone studying or working with children at play.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPlay assessment (Child psychology)xResearch. 0aPlay environmentsxResearch. 0aPlay therapyxResearch. 0aPlayxHistoryzGreat Britain. 0aPlayxHistoryzUnited States. 0aPlayxResearch. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aCoppard, Hattie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickerson, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandscomb, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkes, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Rebekah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary